<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n40060a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n40" href="#n40060a">N40 (VI.B.28B)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n40all.htm#n40060a"> 60(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> changeth his / angels with / folly</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In Tobit, too, we find the idea of the demon or evil angel. In the canonical Old Testament angels may inflict suffering as ministers of God, and Satan may act as accuser or tempter; but they appear as subordinate to God, fulfilling His will; and not as morally evil. The statement that God &ldquo;charged His angels with folly&rdquo; applies to all angels. <small> &ldquo;ANGEL&rdquo; <a name="EBAN" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBAN"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
